<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:35<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720b363682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:35.</label.designator><headtext>Learned treatises</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>With the enactment of <cite.query w-src-number="0287017194" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I51f991607fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(18)</cite.query>, Georgia now admits the contents of a learned treatise if raised upon cross-examination of an expert. <eos/><bos/>An expert may express an opinion about conclusions that may be drawn from a scientific work.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5adede07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017194" w-serial-number="2047737409" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I51fa7bc27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Moore v. Wellstar Health System, Inc.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic5ae14f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] the Court of Appeals reversed the admission into evidence under the learned treatise exception of a document prepared by the American Society of Anesthesiologists. <eos/><bos/>The court declined to extend the scope of the exception in this case because the document was not established as reliable authority; instead, its reliability as a learned treatise was undermined because it was published with a view toward litigation, and thus, a probability of bias existed which undermined the logic in admitting it into evidence over a hearsay objection.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic5adede07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017194" w-serial-number="1992073004" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I51f9df827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Rogers v. State, 202 Ga. App. 595, 415 S.E.2d 49 (1992)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="GAEVIDENCES7:17" w-pub-number="160247" ID="Ic5ae14f07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">§ 7:17</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017194" w-serial-number="1992073004" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000360" ID="I51f9df837fc011ea988285db8533e975">supra,</cite.query> regarding cross examination of expert witnesses.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic5ae14f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017194" w-serial-number="2047737409" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I51fac9e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Moore v. WellStar Health System, Inc., 349 Ga. App. 834, 824 S.E.2d 787 (2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:35<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
